g.ns0:text: \\begin{center}\n{\\Large \\bf Immersions and the space of all translation surfaces}\n\\end{center}

text.tspan: (City College of NY and CUNY Grad Center)

tspan.tspan: Flat surfaces and dynamics on moduli spaces

g.ns0:text:
Let $D$ be a simply connected subset of a translation surface containing the basepoint.

If $S$ is a translation surface, an {\em immersion} of $D$ into $S$
is a continuous map $D \imm S$ which respects the basepoints and the translation structure.
Place a canonical and useful topology on the space\\\\ $\\sM$ of all (pointed) translation surfaces.

For $n \geq 1$, let $R_n \subset \C$ be the $n$-th roots of unity. Let 
$S_n=\C \sm R_n$ with basepoint at the origin.

Then, the sequence of universal covers $\tilde S_n$ converges
to the unit disk.

text.tspan: The topology on the disk bundle:
Topologizing the space of all surfaces:

g.ns0:text: The disk bundle over $\\tM$ is $$\\tE=\\{(\\tilde S, p):p \\in \\tilde S \\in \\tM\\}.$$
We also topologize $\\sE$, the surface bundle over $\\sM$\\ldots

{\bf Theorem.} The topologies on $\tM$, $\tE$, $\sM$, and $\sE$
are second countable and Hausdorff.

{\bf Theorem.} For any $\epsilon>0$, the set of surfaces in $\sM$ or $\tM$ for which 
the basepoint has an open $\epsilon$-neighborhood isometric to the open
$\epsilon$-ball in the plane is compact.

Immersions place a partial order on the space $\tM$ of all simply connected translation surfaces.

{\bf Theorem.} The set $\tM \cup \{0\}$, where $0$ denotes the degenerate, single point ``translation surface''
is a \\
complete lattice, i.e., each subset of $\tM \cup \{0\}$ has a supremum and an infimum
in $\tM \cup \{0\}$.

Straight-line flows on $\tM$, $\tE$, $\sM$, and $\sE$
are continuous wherever defined. 

The $\GL(2,\R)$ actions such as
$\GL(2,\R) \times \sM \to \sM$
are jointly continuous.

{\bf Theorem.} If $S_n \to S$ in $\sM$, and there is a sequence 
$\phi_n:S_n \to S_n$ of affine automorphisms whose\\
derivatives
converge and so that the images of the basepoints converge
to $(S,p) \in \sE$, then $S$ has an affine automorphism with the limiting
deriviative\\
which sends the basepoint to $p$.

{\bf Corollary to work of Trevi\~no\\
(in the spirit of Masur's Criterion).} \\
Suppose $S$ is a translation surface of area one. If there is a sequence of times $t_n \to \infty$
and a sequence of basepoints $s_n$ of $S$ so that under the Teichmuller flow
$g^{t_n}(S,s_n)$ converges to a unit area surface in $\sM$, then the vertical
straight line flow is uniquely ergodic.

{\bf Demo Theorem.} \\
Suppose $S_n$ converges to $S$ in $\sM$. Let $p \in S$.

If the straight-line flow in direction $\theta$ satisfies \\
$F_\theta^t(p)=p$, then there are sequences
$\theta_n \to \theta$, and $t_n \to t$, and $p_n$ so that $(S_n,p_n) \to (S,p)$
so that for $n$ sufficiently large $F_{\theta_n}^{t_n}(p_n)=p_n$.
{\\bf Exercise.} If $\\tilde S_1$ and $\\tilde S_2$ are simply connected translation surfaces and $\\tilde S_1 \\imm \\tilde S_2$ and $\\tilde S_2 \\imm \\tilde S_1$ then $\\tilde S_1=\\tilde S_2$.
